<!DOCTYPE assessment PUBLIC "-//Carnegie Mellon University//DTD Inline Assessment MathML 1.4//EN" "http://oli.cmu.edu/dtd/oli_inline_assessment_mathml_1_4.dtd"><assessment xmlns:cmd="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/content/metadata/2.1/" id="contrast_systemic_pulmonary_vasculature_DIGT2-34-37-a"><title>tutor</title><page id="bd7b59c6368e428f97ba449aca47a86d"><title>Assessment Page Title</title><question id="q1"><body><p id="abcf0f56ebb0c45a298671d09e4b50988">Which of the following is the most common path for blood to move from the left ventricle to the right atrium?</p></body><multiple_choice shuffle="true" select="single" id="c258f1cd8f9d472eb48a7782f3553e00" labels="false"><choice value="a">artery, arterioles, capillaries, venules, veins</choice><choice value="b">arterioles, arteries, capillaries, venules, veins</choice><choice value="c">veins, venules, capillaries, arterioles, arteries</choice><choice value="d">capillaries, arterioles, venules, arteries, veins</choice></multiple_choice><part id="q1_p1"><skillref idref="describe_path_blood_heart_SKILL" /><response match="a" score="1"><feedback><p id="ac2aaf5a567b5489ca2163d990208901f">Correct. Blood moves through the arterial circulation, into capillaries, and then through the venous circulation. To help you remember the sequence, notice that often the longer the name, the smaller the structure.</p></feedback></response><response match="b" score="0"><feedback><p id="ae3f65ca18f8a4647b457bc8e126fcdbe">Incorrect. Although the arterial tree is the first vessels encountered by blood, arterioles are not first.</p></feedback></response><response match="c" score="0"><feedback><p id="ad042fc31670c41d39f5c9e6be20616cf">Incorrect. This is the opposite of the normal flow pathway.</p></feedback></response><response match="d" score="0"><feedback><p id="aa5b1841cc7614f679b698c7e9163cfcd">Incorrect. The capillaries are the midway point of the circuit, not the beginning.</p></feedback></response></part></question></page></assessment>
